From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
Date: Mon, 18 May 2026 09:00:00
Subject: [PATCH] respected external hiding of macOS title bar buttons

QCocoaWindow::updateTitleBarButtons used to drive .hidden on every
standard window button on each call, both to YES and to NO. Make it
only force .hidden = YES when Qt actually wants the buttons hidden
(all of them disabled, or Qt::FramelessWindowHint), and leave the
property alone otherwise. Apps that draw their own traffic-light
replacements can then call [button setHidden:YES] once and have it
stay sticky.

Why this regressed between Qt 6.2 and 6.11:

* 4c78ef80ca7 (Qt 6.3, Sep 2021) — macOS: Handle window titlebar
  buttons independently from style mask. Stopped controlling button
  presence through NSWindowStyleMask{Closable,Miniaturizable,Resizable}
  bits and started managing visibility through per-button .hidden and
  .enabled instead. Those style mask bits also drive non-button
  behavior (programmatic minimize, edge resize), so they are now
  always on and the buttons are individually hidden via a new
  updateTitleBarButtons function. Up to this point Qt never touched
  .hidden on standard buttons, so external setHidden:YES was sticky.

* 1bde2036051 (Qt 6.6, Mar 2023, QTBUG-104905) — macOS: Disable
  interaction for modally blocked transient parent windows. Wired
  updateTitleBarButtons to QEvent::WindowBlocked / WindowUnblocked
  via windowEvent, and added a branch inside it that forces
  hideButtons = false when the parent is blocked by a modal sheet.
  The combination flips .hidden back to NO on every modal attach
  and detach, undoing any externally applied setHidden:YES.

In tdesktop the media-view overlay paints its own traffic lights
and calls setHidden:YES on the three standard window buttons after
show. When Save As opens a window-modal NSSavePanel, Qt receives
WindowBlocked, updateTitleBarButtons sets .hidden = NO on all three
buttons, and they remain visible after the sheet is dismissed.

The change is narrowly scoped — only the unhide branch is removed.
Qt still controls .enabled normally, .hidden = YES still happens
when Qt wants the buttons gone, and the style mask is untouched.
The only behavioral loss is that buttons no longer auto-reappear
when an app removes FramelessWindowHint or CustomizeWindowHint at
runtime; such apps can call setHidden:NO themselves.

diff --git a/src/plugins/platforms/cocoa/qcocoawindow.mm b/src/plugins/platforms/cocoa/qcocoawindow.mm
--- a/src/plugins/platforms/cocoa/qcocoawindow.mm
+++ b/src/plugins/platforms/cocoa/qcocoawindow.mm
@@ -713,9 +713,17 @@ void QCocoaWindow::updateTitleBarButtons(Qt::WindowFlags windowFlags)
         hideButtons &= !enabled;
     }
 
-    // Hide buttons in case we disabled all of them
-    for (const auto &[button, buttonHint] : buttons)
-        [m_view.window standardWindowButton:button].hidden = hideButtons;
+    // Hide buttons in case we disabled all of them, or if the window is
+    // frameless. Never actively unhide: applications may keep the standard
+    // buttons hidden (for example to draw their own traffic lights), and
+    // Qt's modal-blocking path used to flip them back to visible on every
+    // QEvent::WindowBlocked/WindowUnblocked, which broke such setups.
+    const bool wantHide = hideButtons
+        || bool(windowFlags & Qt::FramelessWindowHint);
+    if (wantHide) {
+        for (const auto &[button, buttonHint] : buttons)
+            [m_view.window standardWindowButton:button].hidden = YES;
+    }
 }
 
 void QCocoaWindow::setWindowFlags(Qt::WindowFlags flags)
